## Day 25 — 11 Jun 2026 · QR Attendance — Design

### What I Did
Designed the QR-based attendance flow before writing the implementation: a teacher starts an attendance session, the backend generates a per-session QR code embedding the session ID + tenant ID, students scan it from their own device to mark present. Worked out the endpoint contracts and the QR payload format so Day 26's implementation would be straightforward.

### QR Payload Design
```typescript
// Encode: sessionId + tenantId + timestamp into a compact string,
// decode it back out when a student scans.
export function generateQRCode(sessionId: string, tenantId: string): string {
  const payload = `${sessionId}:${tenantId}:${Date.now()}`
  return Buffer.from(payload).toString('base64url')
}

export function decodeQRCode(qrCode: string): { sid: string; tid: string; ts: number } | null {
  try {
    const decoded = Buffer.from(qrCode, 'base64url').toString('utf-8')
    const [sid, tid, ts] = decoded.split(':')
    if (!sid || !tid || !ts) return null
    return { sid, tid, ts: parseInt(ts, 10) }
  } catch {
    return null
  }
}
```

### Key Learnings
- Embedding the timestamp in the QR payload (not just session ID) means I can expire a QR code server-side without a separate "is this session still active" lookup table — just compare `Date.now() - ts` against a max age
- `base64url` (not plain `base64`) avoids `+`/`/` characters that need URL-encoding if the QR payload is ever embedded in a link instead of scanned as a raw string

