## Day 26 — 12 Jun 2026 · QR Attendance — Shipped + Proprietary License

### What I Did
- Implemented the backend endpoints from Day 25's design: session creation generates and stores the QR code, scan verification decodes it and marks the student present
- Added in-session QR code image display on the teacher's screen — base64 PNG generated server-side via the `qrcode` package, embedded directly as a data URL so there's no extra round trip to fetch an image file
- Added a proprietary `LICENSE` to the repo — the code stays public (for the portfolio/internship visibility) but isn't open for reuse

### Backend Endpoint
```typescript
// src/routes/attendance.ts
let qrCode: string | undefined
if (sessionType === 'qr') {
  qrCode = generateQRCode(id, user.tenant_id)
}

await c.env.DB.prepare(`
  INSERT INTO attendance_sessions (id, tenant_id, teacher_id, class_id, qr_code, created_at)
  VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, datetime('now'))
`).bind(id, user.tenant_id, user.userId, classId, qrCode ?? null).run()
```

### QR Image Display
```typescript
import QRCode from 'qrcode'

attendance.get('/:sessionId/qr-image', async (c) => {
  const session = await getSession(c, c.req.param('sessionId'))
  if (!session?.qr_code) return errorResponse(c, 'No QR code for this session', 404)

  const dataUrl = await QRCode.toDataURL(session.qr_code, { width: 280, margin: 1 })
  return successResponse(c, { qrDataUrl: dataUrl })
})
```

### Key Learnings
- Returning the QR as a base64 data URL instead of a separately-hosted image file keeps the whole "start session → show QR" flow to one request, which matters on a classroom wifi network with 30+ devices about to hit the same endpoint
- A proprietary license doesn't stop the repo from being a useful, visible portfolio piece — `LICENSE` only governs reuse, not visibility, so it's the right call for something I want recruiters to actually read

